HemoGINO: Practical AI Coding Rules

Project Reality
- Source is organized by domain: `src/core_physics/`, `src/architecture/`, `src/data_gen/` (pipelines at package root; mesh/COMSOL/graph **lib** under `data_gen/lib/`), `src/training/`, `src/evaluation/`, `src/utils/`, and `src/tests/`.
- The codebase mixes model training, mesh/graph preprocessing, physics kernels, COMSOL extraction, and validation tooling.
- Large binary and generated artifacts: `data/` (`data_root()`), `outputs/stage_a` / `outputs/stage_b` (checkpoints), `outputs/reports/` (`reports_dir()`), and `comsol_models/`; do not treat them as source code.

Tier Definitions (authoritative)
- Tier 1 (`src/training/train_t1_predictor.py`): Newtonian hemodynamics baseline only (Stage A predictor warm-up).
- Tier 2 (`src/training/train_t2_predictor.py`): adds non-Newtonian rheology (Carreau-Yasuda style behavior; Stage A predictor).
- Tier 3 (`src/training/train_t3_corrector.py`): adds biochemical clot dynamics/coupling on top of flow backbone (Stage B corrector).
- Orchestrator: `python -m src.main {a|b|all}` chains Stage A (predictor) and Stage B (corrector) training.
- Do not assume Tier 3 is the primary stage for kinematic gains; major velocity quality should come from Tier 1/2.

Code Priorities
- Preserve mesh-agnostic behavior: never assume fixed node counts, edge counts, or regular grids.
- Keep boundaries clear: shared physics lives in `core_physics`; GNODE/DEQ/LoRA in `architecture`; graphs/meshes/datagen in `data_gen`.
- Prefer small, local changes over broad refactors unless explicitly requested.
- Keep variable names physically meaningful (`u`, `v`, `p`, `phi`, `mu`, `gamma_dot`) and avoid cryptic abbreviations.

Physics and Modeling Guardrails
- Carreau-Yasuda rheology and Navier-Stokes consistency are central; avoid edits that weaken these constraints without justification.
- For DEQ-related changes, preserve solver stability and convergence behavior.
- For Tier 3 work, preserve the intended split between trainable adaptation layers and physics kernels unless asked otherwise.

Data and File Hygiene
- Ignore and avoid editing cache/derived files (`__pycache__`, `.pytest_cache`, `.pyc`, generated plots/logs/checkpoints).
- Do not create duplicate source files with mixed path separators (for example both `src/file.py` and `src\file.py` variants).
- Keep reusable logic in `src/`; interactive diagnostics live under `src/tools/`; automated tests under `src/tests/`.

Testing Expectations
- Any meaningful logic change should include or update focused pytest coverage.
- For physics kernels and extraction code, validate both numerical sanity and shape/index safety.
- When touching training or data pipelines, run the smallest relevant test subset first, then expand if needed.

Documentation and Readability
- Prefer concise docstrings/comments that explain why (not obvious what).
- Keep equations plain text or LaTeX-compatible text where helpful, but prioritize clarity over notation density.
- When behavior changes, update nearby docs or comments so phase/tier intent stays clear.
